merged branch marekkalnik/curly-brackets (PR #9)Commitsn-------nn4fc0538 Fixer for newlines after/before curly bracketsnnDiscussionn----------nnCurly bracketsnnHi,nnThanks for making this tool public, it's great!nnI've added a fixer for curly brackets:n* add newline after class and function declarationsn* remove newline after control statementsnnI've also added a basic test for that.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-18T07:01:24ZnnThat does not work as we don't have the same rule for anonymous functions. So, you exclude those from matching.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-18T07:05:15ZnnIt would close #6nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-18T07:43:37ZnnThanks for the comments! I'll fix it in the evening.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-18T20:17:06ZnnI've fixed the errors and rebased against master. Quick question - should I recompile the phar? It seems to me that phars are likely to generate multiple conflicts so I think it should be rather the repository manager that does that, to limit the negative impacts.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-19T06:44:41ZnnYes, I'm going to manage the phar re-compilation myself.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-19T06:50:02ZnnTest your code on Symfony, you will see that it does not work as expected. It also looks like this code slows the whole process a lot.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby umpirsky at 2012-05-19T08:52:03Znn@fabpot Does the speed matters?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-19T09:01:16Znn@umpirsky not really, except if it becomes overly slow. I suspect that this change makes things very slow because it changes a lot of things that it should not. So, when it works as expected, it should be fast enough. We will see.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-05-19T11:02:29Znn@fabpot a solution to ease the phar compilation could be to do it the way Composer uses: removing the phar from the repo and compiling it using a hook. It requires having a server hosting the phar though.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-19T11:59:31ZnnI've ran it on a bundle of mine and I worked fine. But it was before adding the treatment of multiple spaces. I'll run it on Symfony and come back with a fix.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-19T12:31:23Znn@stof: That's indeed a good idea. Anywhere I can see the code for Composer?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-19T12:32:47ZnnFixed. I'll see what can I do for the performance, but I don't think there's much that can be done here.nnI've also run in a special case - it's a test fixture (from old 2.0 so I don't know if it still exists) :nclass InvalidConstraintValidator {}nnI guess this should not be modified?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-05-19T12:33:38Znn@Seldaek pingnn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-19T12:45:16ZnnI've just tried on Symfony master and here is change it tries to do:nn-public function __construct($id, $name) {n+public function __construct($id, $name)n+n+n+{nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-05-19T14:04:11Znn@marekkalnik you should add unit tests applying the fixer on correct curly braces, to ensure it does not messes them.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-19T14:15:54Znn@stof Ok, I'll add some tests on correct code (one already added). I've ran it on symfony master, seems ok. CodeSniffer reports no brackets errors but one with do {} while (). I guess I'll need a separate function for that statement.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-20T13:58:10ZnnI've added some tests, tested it on symfony master (seems fine) and refactored the code a bit.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-20T14:29:31ZnnI've tested against Symfony master and indeed the results look fine for me.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-20T14:31:05ZnnBefore I merge, can you remove the change on the `phar` and squash your commits? Thanks.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby fabpot at 2012-05-20T15:27:16ZnnFYI, I've just renamed the repository to `PHP-CS-Fixer`.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby marekkalnik at 2012-05-20T15:35:08ZnnStashed.n

merged branch umpirsky/include-fixer (PR #64)Commitsn-------nnd14d115 Include fixer v2.nedd500a Implemented include fixer.nnDiscussionn----------nnInclude fixernnAt first, I wanted to implement removing outer braces for all cases, but it turned out that there are too many cases and dealing with recursive regex would lead to unnecessary complexity and would probably be slower. So I implemented simplified version. It will also replace double with single quotes and fix spacing.nnSome examples:nn1. `include   foo.php` => `include 'foo.php'`n2. `include (  Buzz/foo-Bar.php )` => `include 'Buzz/foo-Bar.php'`n3. `require_once  (__DIR__.('foo.php'))` => `require_once (__DIR__.('foo.php'))`nnFor cases like 3. it only fix white spaces between include and path leaving brackets as they are.nnThis should fix issue [#47](https://github.com/fabpot/PHP-CS-Fixer/issues/47).nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby umpirsky at 2012-06-07T06:51:16ZnnAny reason not to merge this?nnPing @fabpot.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-06-07T07:48:01Znn@umpirsky the main reason is probably the organization of the Symfony Live :)nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby umpirsky at 2012-06-07T07:50:36ZnnYeah, I had that in mind. But I guess it's not only @fabpot who can merge?nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-06-07T08:52:02Znnit is.n

merged branch Seldaek/psr0 (PR #88)Commitsn-------nn45a56ae Add a Psr0Fixer for class / file names matchingnf57888f Add a PSR-0 levelnnDiscussionn----------nnPSR-0 fixer for mistakes in class namesnnIt fixes bad case, but for the rest it just throws an exception to notify the user, because it's impossible to fix automatically. I don't know if this is ok with the philosophy of tool or not.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-06-20T17:44:20ZnnChanging the class name is a bad idea IMO. What if the other parts of the code use the same case than the class name ? They will still trigger it with this case, and so failing on case-sensitive filesystems. the definition of the class is the place where the case could be different without breaking the autoloading.nso a PSR-0 fixer would need to analyze the whole codebase, not only a file.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-06-20T17:47:53ZnnWell if they use the wrong case in other parts of the code, the code should already be failing. The point of this anyway is to highlight an error, this is pretty rare that it goes unnoticed, but it happens that it sneaks into some rarely used parts of a library.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby stof at 2012-06-20T17:51:58Znn@Seldaek the code would be failing only if the developer is on a case-sensitive filesystem. A common case for such errors is developign on MacOS or Windows, which are case insensitive and breaking things when deploying on Linux.nn---------------------------------------------------------------------------nnby Seldaek at 2012-06-20T17:54:31ZnnYeah my point is that this will show you that you have an error (I'd hope people check the diff before committing..). Instead of fixing I can also always throw an exception, so you notice it better, and you can go and fix it in other places yourself if you messed up, or rename the file if the filename is incorrect.nnI can also change it to just output a warning if the exception is too violent. Up to @fabpot.n

merged branch pylebecq/fix-braces (PR #109)Commitsn-------nn65d2887 Fixed braces fixer for else if statements.nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed braces fixer for else if statements.nnHey there,nnI found out a weird case with some else if statements. It is related to the braces fixer. When it encounters something liken```phpnif (...)n{n// ...n}nelse if (...)n{n// ...n}n```nIt will convert it ton```nif (...) {n// ...n} else { if (...)n// ...n}n```nnWhich is totally wrong. If you have several else if statements, you end up with successive else statements, resulting in a parse error.n

feature #262 Allow to specify path to .php_cs file using --config-file option (localheinz)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 0.4.x-dev branch (closes #262).nnDiscussionn----------nnAllow to specify path to .php_cs file using --config-file optionnnThis PR adds the possibility to specify the path to  the `.php_cs` file using a newly added `--config-file` option.nnThis is very useful if you have a Git `pre-commit` hook similar to the one suggested by [ZF2](https://github.com/zendframework/zf2/blob/master/README-GIT.md#pre-commit-hook-optional), but want to keep the configuration separate from the hook:nn```phpn#!/usr/bin/env phpn<?phpnn$changes = [];nnexec(n'git diff --cached --name-status --diff-filter=ACM',n$changesn);nn$exit = 0;nnarray_walk($changes, function ($change) use (&$exit) {nnif ('D' === substr($change, 0, 1)) {nreturn;n}nn$name = trim(substr(n$change,n1n));nn$extension = pathinfo(n$name,nPATHINFO_EXTENSIONn);nnif (!preg_match('/^ph(p|tml)$/', $extension)) {nreturn;n}nn$output = [];n$return = 0;nnexec(nsprintf(n'php -l %s',nescapeshellarg($name)n),n$output,n$returnn);nnif (0 != $return) {nnecho sprintf(n'Failed parsing: %s: ' . PHP_EOL,n$namen);nnecho implode(PHP_EOL, $output) . PHP_EOL;nn$exit = 1;nreturn;n}nn$output = [];n$return = 0;nnexec(nsprintf(n'vendor/bin/php-cs-fixer fix --verbose --config-file=.php_cs %s',nescapeshellarg($name)n),n$output,n$returnn);nnif (0 != $return) {nnecho sprintf(n'Fixed coding style issues in : %s' . PHP_EOL,n$namen);nnecho implode(PHP_EOL, $output) . PHP_EOL;nn$exit = 1;nreturn;n}n});nnexit($exit);n```nnFixes #251.nnCommitsn-------nne4ceb86 Allow to specify path to .php_cs file using --config-file optionn

bug #336 Ignoring some special cases of functions getting visibility added (jaydiablo)This PR was merged into the 0.4.x-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnIgnoring some special cases of functions getting visibility addednnThis is similar to #332, but this one includes a fix.  When running php-cs-fixer against more procedural style code (no oop) this visibility fixer would add public visibility keyword to the front of the function declarations, causing fatal syntax errors.  I added the test cases from #332, and added some more that I discovered it was processing (that it shouldn't be).nnTo pass these tests, I've modified the fixer to look for the OOP trigger words in what would be considered PHP code, rather than just the entire source content (ignores comments, doc blocks, strings and inline html).  I didn't see any easy way to do this with the regex used, but by using PHP's tokenizer I was able to strip these tokens from the content before the regex is run.nnI had to add <?php tags to all of the tests for this class because otherwise the text is seen as T_INLINE_HTML to the tokenizer.nnCommitsn-------nn9d79607 Ignoring some special cases of functions getting visibility added when not in a class.  With some additional tests, some taken from #332.n
Enhancement: Make path argument optional

bug #345 Enhancement: Make path argument optional (localheinz)This PR was merged into the 0.4.x-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnEnhancement: Make path argument optionalnnSome people - namely the [ZF2](http://github.com/zendframework/zf2) community - have been experiencing failing builds on Travis as a result of https://github.com/fabpot/PHP-CS-Fixer/pull/342 and the following setup:nn### Steps to reproducenn* requiring `fabpot/php-cs-fixer: dev-master`n* running (note the `.` as `path` argument)nn```n $ vendor/bin/php-cs-fixer fix -v --dry-run .n```nnwhile having a `.php_cs` that specifies directoriesnn   ```phpn   $finder = SymfonyCSFinderDefaultFinder::create()n->in(__DIR__ . '/library')n->in(__DIR__ . '/tests')n->in(__DIR__ . '/bin')n;n```nnand while having files within `__DIR__` (or other directories therein not listed above) that will cause the script to exit with something else than `0` as status.nnBasically, the problem is that the `path` argument is *required*, and in a setup as described above and with the changes introduced in #342, the `.` path gets added to the `Finder` while before #342, it wasn't.nn### SolutionnnEither revert #342 or make the `path` argument optional.nnThis PR makes the `path` argument optional.nnCommitsn-------nn121454e Enhancement: Make path argument optionaln

bug #430 FixCommand - override config dir only if path is set (keradus)This PR was merged into the 0.5.x-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnFixCommand - override config dir only if path is setnnHey!nnLet imagine that I have a project structure:n```n- rootn- An- Bn- Cn```nnIn root dir I have a .php_cs file:n```phpn<?phpnn$config = SymfonyCSConfigConfig::create();n$config->setDir([__DIR__ . /A, __DIR__ . /C, ]);nnreturn $config;n```nnSo I just want to fix A i C subdirs and leave alone B subdir. And I want to do it in config file.nIt is a simple case just to show my problem, I known that I could exclude B subdir, but I have a little to include and a lot to exclude in one project :(nnOK, let run the fixer:n`php-cs-fixer fix` (without path, because I defined it in config file)n? Is it work? No! FixCommand will call again ->setDir method (see: https://github.com/fabpot/PHP-CS-Fixer/blob/master/Symfony/CS/Console/Command/FixCommand.php#L226) with null argument and fixer will crash with msg: `You must call one of in() or append() methods before iterating over a Finder`nnConclusionnLet the fix command override `$config->dir` only if `path` argument was set.nnCommitsn-------nn2ec7994 FixCommand - override config dir only if path is setn

minor #492 Fixed tests on HHVM  (Nyholm)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 0.5.x-dev branch (closes #492).nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed tests on HHVMnnI fixed the errors on on the test suit on HHVM. They are related to HHVM and not this lib. I created workarounds and made a comment about it.nnI also fixed some failures that relied on the order of the fixers returned from `Fixer::getFixers`. When using `usort` on HHVM you can't rely on the order between objects with the same weight.nnThere are still failures that I have not managed to figure out a good workaround for. They are related to the `token_get_all` function. On HHVM `token_get_all` does not return the same output.nExample:n``` phpnn$var = <<<'EOF'n<?phpn$b = <<<'TEXT'nFoo TEXT;nBar1}nnFooFoonTEXT;nEOF;nnvar_dump(token_get_all($var));n```n``` phpn//Prints on PHP 5.5:nnarray(7) {n  [0] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(374)n[1] =>nstring(6) <?phpnn[2] =>nint(1)n  }n  [1] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(310)n[1] =>nstring(2) $bn[2] =>nint(2)n  }n  [2] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(377)n[1] =>nstring(1)  n[2] =>nint(2)n  }n  [3] =>n  string(1) =n  [4] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(377)n[1] =>nstring(1)  n[2] =>nint(2)n  }n  [5] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(378)n[1] =>nstring(10) <<<'TEXT'nn[2] =>nint(2)n  }n  [6] =>n  array(3) {n[0] =>nint(315)n[1] =>nstring(30) Foo TEXT;nBar1}nnFooFoonTEXT;n[2] =>nint(3)n  }n}nn```nn``` phpn//Prints on HHVM:nnarray(6) {n  [0]=>n  array(3) {n[0]=>nint(368)n[1]=>nstring(6) <?phpnn[2]=>nint(1)n  }n  [1]=>n  array(3) {n[0]=>nint(309)n[1]=>nstring(2) $bn[2]=>nint(2)n  }n  [2]=>n  array(3) {n[0]=>nint(371)n[1]=>nstring(1)  n[2]=>nint(2)n  }n  [3]=>n  string(1) =n  [4]=>n  array(3) {n[0]=>nint(371)n[1]=>nstring(1)  n[2]=>nint(2)n  }n  [5]=>n  array(3) {n[0]=>nint(372)n[1]=>nstring(10) <<<'TEXT'nn[2]=>nint(2)n  }n}n```nnCommitsn-------nn2f85f17 Fixed tests on HHVMn

feature #476 TrailingCommaInMultiLineArrayFixer (sstok)This PR was merged into the 0.5.x-dev branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnTrailingCommaInMultiLineArrayFixernn|Q|A  |n|---  |---|n|Bug Fix? |n  |n|New Feature? |yes|n|BC Breaks?   |n  |n|Deprecations?|n  |n|Tests Pass?  |yes|n|Fixed Tickets|   |n|License  |MIT|n|Doc PR   |   |nnThis adds the TrailingCommaInMultiLineArrayFixer: PHP Multi-line arrays should have a trailing commannThere is only minor problem that I was unable to resolve, when you have an array like.nn```phpn<?phpnn$x = array(narray());nn?>n```nnThe result will be.nn```phpn<?phpnn$x = array(narray(),);nn?>n```nnWhich is not fully correct, but the detection for this is problamatic.nnWe can't just add a new line, as that will move the closing brace to the beginging of the line.nAnd looking for the previous whitespace as something like `($y ? 'yes' : 'no')` will detect the wrong whitespace for indenting.nnSo we can either detect the missing new-line and add it, and let a nother fixer (or manual change) fix this.nOr leave this as it is now, and try to fix this later using either another fixer or improving this fixer.nnCommitsn-------nn8d04fca add TrailingCommaInMultiLineArrayFixern

implemented YodaConditions fixer

feature #611 implemented YodaConditions fixer (bgotink)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.0.x-dev branch (closes #611).nnDiscussionn----------nnimplemented YodaConditions fixernnSee #598.nnI know the code is missing comments, but I wanted feedback on the code first.nnModus operandi:nnThe documentation on operator precedence ([here][precedense_doc]) shows PHP has two different levels of comparison:n- `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=`n- `==`, `!=`, `===`, `!==`, `<>`nThe latter of the two has a lower precedence.nnThe fixer does the following for both kinds of comparison, with the higher precedence coming first:n- iterate backwards over the tokens until a comparison is foundn  - find the left-hand side and right-hand side of the comparisonn  - run the entire process over both left-hand and right-hand sidesn  - if the left-hand isn't a simple expression and the right-hand is, switch sidesn  - skip all tokens that were part of this comparisonnnIt looks for the left-hand and right-hand sides by going backward/forward starting at the comparison itself, using:n- define `$level` as the level of parentheses the current token is in, with the comparison token being at `0`n- if `$level` is below zero, we've found the endn- if `$level` isn't zero, we haven't found the endn- if the current token has a lower precedence, we've found the endn- if  the current token is a `,` or `;`, we've found the endn- if the current token is a keyword like `return`, `case`, `throw`, `goto`, we've found the endnnDeciding whether or not a side is simple is currently implemented as checking whether the side is an integer (`T_LNUMBER`), a floating point number (`T_DNUMBER`), a string( `T_CONSTANT_ENCAPSED_STRING`) or any keyword (`T_STRING`).nn[precedense_doc]: http://php.net/manual/en/language.operators.precedence.phpnnCommitsn-------nn56923af implemented YodaConditions fixern

'bar', PHP_EOL;nn  ---------- end diff ----------n```nnCommitsn-------nn23c07bb FixersResolver - make class more state aware and enhance it's testsne75c985 Fix README and some codes.n6876726 FixersResolver - simplify codenf3c966f Fix `fix` command to handle `--fixers` option when contains include and excluding fixersn

Add a way to disable all default filters and really provide a whitelist

minor #731 Add a way to disable all default filters and really provide a whitelist (Seldaek)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.1-dev branch (closes #731).nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd a way to disable all default filters and really provide a whitelistnnI had a big WTF moment because the current readme says this is a whitelist:nn```nreturn SymfonyCSConfigConfig::create()n->fixers(array('indentation', 'elseif'))n->finder($finder)n;n```nnExcept it's not, it will first add all `symfony` level fixers and then add those two. So I added a new level to allow choosing exactly what you want from a config file (previously it was only possible with cli args I think).nnCommitsn-------nn669e8f8 Add a way to disable all default filters and really provide a whitelistn

Enable caching of composer downloads on TravisThe new docker-based infrastructure allows to use the cache for public repos too.

minor #944 Enable caching of composer downloads on Travis (stof)This PR was submitted for the 1.4 branch but it was merged into the 1.5 branch instead (closes #944).nnDiscussionn----------nnEnable caching of composer downloads on TravisnnThis is possible thanks to 2 changes:nn- the new docker-based infrastructure allows to use the cache for public repos too.n- since several months, Composer is smart enough to fallback to a source install in case it cannot download the dist, avoiding to break the build in case the Github API rate limit is reached on the Travis VMnnAnd thanks to the usage of the cache, most downloads will not count in the API rate limit because they will never reach Github (only new versions will be downloaded when one of the dependencies makes a new release).nnNote that the PR build will not show any improvement yet, because PR builds are loading the cache of their target branch, and the target branch does not have a cache yet of course.nnThe target of this PR is 1.4 so that all maintained branches will get this improvement.nnCommitsn-------nn8663c23 Enable caching of composer downloads on Travisn

Add HeaderCommentFixer

feature #1002 Add HeaderCommentFixer (ajgarlag)This PR was squashed before being merged into the 1.5 branch (closes #1002).nnDiscussionn----------nnAdd HeaderCommentFixernnIn most projects, every php file has a header comment with information about copyright and license. This PR introduces a new fixer to add, rewrite or remove this header comment in order to standarize it. This is a particular fixer, because it needs a configuration parameter, the header text, that varies with the project.nnI made a first implementation where a new method `getHeader` was added to `ConfigInterface`, so the fixer implementing the `ConfigAwareInterface` could read the header text, but this new method was BC break.nnIn my second implementation, the header is statically set into the `HeaderCommentFixer` class so it can be set from the config file without any BC break. If you think there is a better way to accomplish this, ping me.nnThe fixer only modifies files with `php` extension starting with a `T_OPEN_TAG` token. It will add a header comment, or rewrite the existing one to update the header text. If the header text is empty, it will remove the header comment.nnThis PR adds the fixer to the `.php_cs` config file for this project. Another PR #1003 has been opened to update the header comments in this project after running this new fixer.nnCommitsn-------nn04c8137 Add HeaderCommentFixern

Prevent token collection corruption by fixersThis prevents replacing token content with unrelated content (hacky fix)nin places which should override tokens. Given that the Tokens collectionnis cached and will be reused by the following fixer, a corruptedncollection could break the following fixer as it expects token types tonbe valid.n
Fix collection corruption in fixers

bug #1151 Prevent token collection corruption by fixers (stof, keradus)This PR was merged into the 1.7 branch.nnDiscussionn----------nnPrevent token collection corruption by fixersnnThis prevents replacing token content with unrelated content (hacky fix) in places which should override tokens. Given that the Tokens collection is cached and will be reused by the following fixer, a corrupted collection could break the following fixer as it expects token types to be valid.nnThe goal is to prevent having to deal with cases like that: https://github.com/FriendsOfPHP/PHP-CS-Fixer/pull/1097#discussion_r27307639nnReplaces #1098nnCommitsn-------nnf0583ad Fix collection corruption in fixersn2732e86 Prevent token collection corruption by fixersn

Fixed error handler to respect current error_reporting

minor #1238 Fixed error handler to respect current error_reporting (JanJakes)This PR was submitted for the master branch but it was merged into the 1.9 branch instead (closes #1238).nnDiscussionn----------nnFixed error handler to respect current error_reportingnnIgnoring current error_reporting can break any code relying on the unfamous `@` operator. Lines like `@unlink($file) // @ - file may not exist` are very common.nnQuoting from http://php.net/manual/en/language.operators.errorcontrol.php:n> If you have set a custom error handler function with set_error_handler() then it will still get called, but this custom error handler can (and should) call error_reporting() which will return 0 when the call that triggered the error was preceded by an @.nnCommitsn-------nnc2e9f6b Fixed error handler to respect current error_reportingn

minor #2138 composer.json - disallow to run on PHP 7.2+ (keradus)This PR was merged into the 1.12 branch.nnDiscussionn----------nncomposer.json - disallow to run on PHP 7.2+nnRequesting for comments.nnAs all new 7.X versions could brings new tokens (or reuse existing token in different place) it's impossible to say that we will properly handle those new tokens with existing code.nThat could lead to wrong changes in file, ignoring file or crashing the fixer.nInstead, let not guess that probably we will works on 7.2+ code, but when we will be sure we do just update supported PHP versions.nnNice side effect is that we would be able to introduce new transformers for new tokens without breaking BC and bumping MAJOR version.nnCommitsn-------nnd6ec4dd composer.json - disallow to run on PHP 7.2+n
